,"about 1381":"about 1381","ABT    1400":"about 1400","1400":"1400","1377":"1377","Abt 1396":"about 1396","1396":"1396","1394":"1394","1381":"1381","about 1394":"about 1394","Llanwrthwl, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llanwrthwl, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Cantref, Breconshire, Wales":"Cantref, Breconshire, Wales","Glyntawe, Breconshire, Wales":"Glyntawe, Breconshire, Wales","Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: occupational name for a cobbler.","Slovenian: nickname for a talkative person, from <i>lapati</i> ‘to babble’, or a topographic name from dialect <i>lap</i> ‘abyss’. Compare   Lapp   4."],"variants":[{"name":"Lapp","meanings":["German, English, and Dutch: from Middle High German and Middle English <i>lappe</i>, Middle Dutch <i>lap</i> ‘cloth, patch, rag’, a metonymic occupational name for a mender of clothes or shoes, or a nickname given to someone who wore ragged clothes or garments with loose folds, flaps, or hanging sleeves, or who had fleshy folds of skin on his face, neck, or body.","German: nickname for a simple-minded person, from Middle Low German <i>lappe</i> ‘fool’. This surname (in any of the two possible senses; see also 1 above) is also found in France (mainly Alsace, also Lorraine).","English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>lappe</i> ‘burdock’, perhaps for someone with a prickly character."]}]},{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(Welsh)  See  Llewelyn ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewelyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]}]},{"name":"Ddu","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 竇, meaning ‘hole’ in ancient Chinese: (i) adopted as a surname by Yue Zhu and Yue Long, two sons of Shao Kang, the sixth king of the Xia dynasty (2070–1600  BC ). Yue Zhu and Yue Long are said to have adopted Dou (竇) (meaning ‘hole’) as a surname because their pregnant grandmother had escaped from a rebellion through a hole in the wall before giving birth to their father, Shao Kang, who later recaptured the throne. (ii) traced back to the Dou (竇) family from the Di ethnic group and some other families from the Xianbei ethnic group in ancient China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 豆, denoting an ancient stemmed cup of bowl: (i) traced back to some inhabitants in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) adopted as the surname by the Chi Xiao Dou (赤小豆) and Dou Lu (豆盧) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 鈄, referring to a type of ancient vessel for drinking wine: said to be borne by the descendants of the Duke Kang of Qi (died 379  BC ), who was ousted from his throne in the state of Qi and sent into exile. It was said that he was forced to use the vessel Dou (鈄) to cook food during his exile, and some of his descendants inherited Dou as the surname to memorize this period."],"variants":[{"name":"Du","meanings":["‘Wealthy’."]},{"name":"Dau","meanings":["From Old Norse <i>dagr</i> ‘day’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Llywelyn Ddu ap Dafydd was born about 1381, in Glyntawe, Breconshire, Wales. She had at least 3 sons with Llywelyn \" Ddu\" ap Dafydd."},"et":{"about 1381–":"umbes 1381–Surnud","1377–Male":"1377–Surnud","1394–Male":"1394–Surnud","1396–Male":"1396–Surnud","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1381–Female":"1381–Surnud","about 1381":"umbes 1381","ABT    1400":"umbes 1400","1400":"1400","1377":"1377","Abt 1396":"umbes 1396","1396":"1396","1394":"1394","1381":"1381","about 1394":"umbes 1394","Llanwrthwl, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llanwrthwl, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Cantref, Breconshire, Wales":"Cantref, Breconshire, Wales","Glyntawe, Breconshire, Wales":"Glyntawe, Breconshire, Wales","Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1381–":"noin 1381–Kuollut","1377–Male":"1377–Kuollut","1394–Male":"1394–Kuollut","1396–Male":"1396–Kuollut","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","1381–Female":"1381–Kuollut","about 1381":"noin 1381","ABT    1400":"noin 1400","1400":"1400","1377":"1377","Abt 1396":"noin 1396","1396":"1396","1394":"1394","1381":"1381","about 1394":"noin 1394","Llanwrthwl, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llanwrthwl, Breconshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cantref, Breconshire, Wales":"Cantref, Breconshire, Wales","Glyntawe, Breconshire, Wales":"Glyntawe, Breconshire, Wales","Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1381–":"environ 1381–Décédée","1377–Male":"1377–Décédé","1394–Male":"1394–Décédé","1396–Male":"1396–Décédé","1400–Male":"1400–Décédé","1381–Female":"1381–Décédée","about 1381":"environ 1381","ABT    1400":"environ 1400","1400":"1400","1377":"1377","Abt 1396":"environ 1396","1396":"1396","1394":"1394","1381":"1381","about 1394":"environ 1394","Llanwrthwl, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llanwrthwl, Breconshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Cantref, Breconshire, Wales":"Cantref, Breconshire, Galles","Glyntawe, 